{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492523"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.78,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man is being investigated for infertility. As part of the examination he is found to have a 6 cm swelling in the right side of his scrotum. This swelling is smooth-surfaced, fluctuant, non-tender and spherical in shape. The vas is easily palpable. The left testis and that side of the scrotum appear normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is be most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compressibility","Reducibility","Transilluminability","Detection of a fluid thrill","Diminution in size when lying down"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis swelling is almost certainly a hydrocele. Since most hydroceles are idiopathic and contain clear fluid, they will usually \u003Cstrong\u003Etransilluminate\u003C/strong\u003E. It is important to note that this finding applies to other cystic scrotal masses such as spermatoceles. In children it is possible for inguinal-scrotal hernias to transilluminate - but this is uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydroceles are unlikely to be \u003Cstrong\u003Ereducible\u003C/strong\u003E. Such a finding would be more typical of a hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is unlikely to be any \u003Cstrong\u003Ediminution in size\u003C/strong\u003E when the patient is lying down. - Infantile hydroceles may still communicate with the peritoneal cavity and might be less full when the patient lies flat - but that is less likely in the adult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efluid thrill\u003C/strong\u003E describes a physical sign elicited in the presence of fluid (ascites) within the abdominal cavity. It is not a test for the detection of fluid in the scrotum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydroceles may sometimes \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompress\u003C/strong\u003E - but this is only likely when the hydrocele is a communicating type.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydroceles are a cystic mass that can transilluminate"],"references":["Huzaifa M, Moreno MA. Hydrocele. [Updated 2021 Jul 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559125/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1089"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c